{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17569952","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17569952"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:35:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:35:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22625"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"22625","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/22625"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.29,0.23,0.3,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15578"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110888"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"15578","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15578"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22625"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93061"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1110"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"41906"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41907"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110888","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/110888"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 80-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a four-day history of left-sided abdominal pain and distension. He has been vomiting and able to eat very little. His medical history includes hypertension and type 2 diabetes mellitus. His medications include perindopril and metformin. He does not smoke and drinks one can of beer daily.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears distressed with pain. His pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 130/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 97% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. His upper abdomen is distended and resonant to percussion. Bowel sounds are present. No other abnormalities are found.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA CT scan is performed (Image 1, 2).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pancreatic pseudocyst","Acute gastric dilatation","Diabetic gastroparesis","Gastric volvulus","Splenic cyst"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EGastric volvulus is a rare but serious condition where the stomach rotates abnormally, leading to obstruction and potential ischaemia. It typically presents in elderly patients with predisposing anatomical factors such as diaphragmatic defects or lax gastric ligaments. The condition can be acute or chronic, with acute presentations requiring urgent surgical intervention to prevent gastric necrosis and perforation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGastric volvulus\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct diagnosis. The CT scan shows a massively distended stomach with abnormal positioning consistent with organoaxial rotation (along the stomach\u0027s long axis). The clinical presentation of severe abdominal pain, distension, and vomiting in an elderly patient, combined with the characteristic imaging findings, confirms this diagnosis. The resonant percussion over the upper abdomen reflects the air-filled, obstructed stomach.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPancreatic pseudocyst\u003C/strong\u003E would appear as a fluid-filled collection adjacent to the pancreas on CT imaging, typically following acute pancreatitis. The patient has no history of pancreatitis, and the imaging shows gastric distension rather than a peripancreatic collection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute gastric dilatation\u003C/strong\u003E can occur postoperatively or in critically ill patients but typically shows uniform gastric distension without the rotational abnormality seen in volvulus. The CT would show a dilated stomach in normal anatomical position without evidence of rotation or obstruction at a specific point.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiabetic gastroparesis\u003C/strong\u003E causes delayed gastric emptying and can lead to distension, but it develops gradually over time in patients with longstanding diabetes. The CT would show food debris and fluid in a dilated stomach but without the acute rotational changes or severe obstruction pattern seen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESplenic cyst\u003C/strong\u003E would appear as a well-defined fluid collection within or adjacent to the spleen. The clinical presentation would not include gastric symptoms, and the CT findings clearly show gastric pathology rather than splenic abnormality.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Gastric volvulus presents with Borchardt\u0027s triad: severe epigastric pain, retching without vomiting, and inability to pass a nasogastric tube.","Organoaxial volvulus (rotation along the long axis) is the most common type and is associated with diaphragmatic defects in elderly patients.","CT imaging shows a massively distended stomach with abnormal positioning and the \u0027whirl sign\u0027 at the point of rotation."],"references":["Bauman ZM, Evans CH. Volvulus. Surg Clin N Am 2018; 98:973\u201393. Avaiable from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30243456/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93061"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22625"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"22006"},{"type":"media","id":"22007"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}